HOUSE BILL 1375
J5 6lr1665
HB 1268/25 – HGO CF 6lr3651
By: Delegates Howard, Adams, Anderson, Arentz, Baker, Beauchamp, Buckel,
Ciliberti, Fair, Hornberger, Hutchinson, Jacobs, McComas, Miller,
T. Morgan, Reilly, Rose, and Wivell
Introduced and read first time: February 13, 2026
Assigned to: Health
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Health Insurance – Lyme Disease and Related Tick–Borne Illnesses –
3 Long–Term Antibiotic Treatment
4 FOR the purpose of requiring certain insurers, nonprofit health service plans, and health
5 maintenance organizations to provide certain coverage for the full length of
6 long–term antibiotic treatment of Lyme disease and related tick–borne illnesses
7 under certain circumstances; prohibiting certain insurers, nonprofit health service
8 plans, and health maintenance organizations from placing a quantitative limit on or
9 denying coverage for benefits required under this Act; and generally relating to
10 health insurance coverage for long–term antibiotic treatment for Lyme disease and
11 related tick–borne illnesses.
12 BY adding to
13 Article – Insurance
14 Section 15–864
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2017 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – Insurance
20 15–864.
21 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
22 INDICATED.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *hb1375*

2 HOUSE BILL 1375
1 (2) “CLINICAL DIAGNOSIS” MEANS THE OBSERVATION BY A LICENSED
2 PHYSICIAN OF SIGNS AND SYMPTOMS COMPATIBLE WITH ACUTE, PERSISTENT, OR
3 CHRONIC INFECTION OR OTHER CHRONIC MANIFESTATIONS OF LYME DISEASE.
4 (3) (I) “LONG–TERM ANTIBIOTIC TREATMENT” MEANS THE
5 ADMINISTRATION OF ORAL, INTRAMUSCULAR, OR INTRAVENOUS ANTIBIOTIC
6 MEDICATIONS FOR LONGER THAN 4 WEEKS.
7 (II) “LONG–TERM ANTIBIOTIC TREATMENT” INCLUDES
8 SEPARATE AND COMBINATION ADMINISTRATIONS OF ANTIBIOTIC MEDICATIONS.
9 (4) “LYME DISEASE” INCLUDES ONE OR MORE OF THE FOLLOWING:
10 (I) THE CLINICAL DIAGNOSIS OF A PATIENT BY A LICENSED
11 PHYSICIAN OF THE PRESENCE OF SIGNS OR SYMPTOMS COMPATIBLE WITH AN ACUTE
12 INFECTION WITH BORRELIA BURGDORFERI;
13 (II) LATE–STAGE, PERSISTENT, OR CHRONIC INFECTION WITH
14 BORRELIA BURGDORFERI;
15 (III) COMPLICATIONS RELATED TO AN INFECTION WITH
16 BORRELIA BURGDORFERI;
17 (IV) AN INFECTION BY OTHER STRAINS OF BORRELIA THAT
18 BECOME IDENTIFIED OR RECOGNIZED BY THE CENTERS FOR DISEASE CONTROL
19 AND PREVENTION AS A CAUSE OF LYME DISEASE;
20 (V) AN INFECTION THAT MEETS THE SURVEILLANCE CRITERIA
21 FOR LYME DISEASE SET FORTH BY THE CENTERS FOR DISEASE CONTROL AND
22 PREVENTION; AND
23 (VI) A CLINICAL DIAGNOSIS OF LYME DISEASE THAT DOES NOT
24 MEET THE SURVEILLANCE CRITERIA SET FORTH BY THE CENTERS FOR DISEASE
25 CONTROL AND PREVENTION BUT PRESENTS OTHER ACUTE, PERSISTENT, OR
26 CHRONIC SIGNS OR SYMPTOMS OF LYME DISEASE AS DETERMINED BY A LICENSED
27 PHYSICIAN, WHETHER THAT DIAGNOSIS IS BASED ONLY ON KNOWLEDGE OBTAINED
28 THROUGH MEDICAL HISTORY AND PHYSICAL EXAMINATION OR IN CONJUNCTION
29 WITH TESTING THAT PROVIDES SUPPORTIVE DATA OF THE DIAGNOSIS.
30 (5) “RELATED TICK–BORNE ILLNESS” MEANS BARTONELLOSIS,
31 BABESIOSIS, EHRLICHIOSIS, ANAPLASMOSIS, PIROPLASMOSIS, OR ANY OTHER
32 TICK–BORNE ILLNESS THAT MAY BE ASSOCIATED WITH LYME DISEASE.

HOUSE BILL 1375 3
1 (6) “THERAPEUTIC PURPOSE” MEANS THE USE OF ANTIBIOTICS TO
2 CONTROL THE SYMPTOMS OF LYME DISEASE AND OTHER RELATED
3 TICK–BORNE ILLNESSES.
4 (B) THIS SECTION APPLIES TO:
5 (1) INSURERS AND NONPROFIT HEALTH SERVICE PLANS THAT
6 PROVIDE HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, SURGICAL, OR PHARMACEUTICAL BENEFITS TO
7 INDIVIDUALS OR GROUPS ON AN EXPENSE–INCURRED BASIS UNDER A HEALTH
8 INSURANCE POLICY OR CONTRACT ISSUED OR DELIVERED IN THE STATE; AND
9 (2) HEALTH MAINTENANCE ORGANIZATIONS THAT PROVIDE
10 HOSPITAL, MEDICAL, SURGICAL, OR PHARMACEUTICAL BENEFITS TO INDIVIDUALS
11 OR GROUPS UNDER CONTRACTS THAT ARE ISSUED OR DELIVERED IN THE STATE.
12 (C) IF THE LONG–TERM ANTIBIOTIC TREATMENT OF LYME DISEASE AND
13 RELATED TICK–BORNE ILLNESSES HAS BEEN ORDERED BY A LICENSED TREATING
14 PHYSICIAN FOR THERAPEUTIC PURPOSES, AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION:
15 (1) SHALL PROVIDE COVERAGE FOR THE FULL LENGTH OF THE
16 LONG–TERM ANTIBIOTIC TREATMENT TO BE ADMINISTERED IN THE MANNER
17 PRESCRIBED BY THE LICENSED TREATING PHYSICIAN; AND
18 (2) MAY NOT IMPOSE A QUANTITATIVE LIMITATION ON THE
19 LONG–TERM ANTIBIOTIC TREATMENT.
20 (D) AN ENTITY SUBJECT TO THIS SECTION MAY NOT DENY COVERAGE FOR
21 TREATMENT OTHERWISE ELIGIBLE FOR BENEFITS UNDER THIS SECTION SOLELY
22 BECAUSE THE TREATMENT MAY BE CATEGORIZED AS UNPROVEN, EXPERIMENTAL,
23 OR INVESTIGATIONAL IN NATURE.
24 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall apply to all
25 policies, contracts, and health benefit plans issued, delivered, or renewed in the State on or
26 after January 1, 2027.
27 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
28 January 1, 2027.

